ing countries. While the treatment of conflicting policy positions is objective, the author comes out on the side of unrestricted competition in world markets, including elimination of domestic subsidies to import barriers, the use of economic stockpiles to reduce vulnerability to import disruption, and maintenance of strict environmental pollution standards. The author is optimistic about the long-run outlook for mineral supplies necessary to meet world requirements for economic growth. United States domestic mineral independence may be unnecessary in terms of national security and too costly to consumers and the environment.\u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.9690582\"\u003eView on Fulcrum platform.\u003c\/a\u003e\u003c\/div\u003e","identifier":"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.9690582","language":"eng","modified":"2025-08-16T08:24:10Z","published":"1987-01-01","publisher":"University of Michigan Press","subject":"Economics:International Economics"},"links":[{"rel":"self","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/vq27zr83m/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/vq27zr83m/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/tx31qn30d/download","type":"application/pdf"}],"images":[{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/z316q488p/full/full/0/default.jpg","type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/z316q488p/full/200,/0/default.jpg","width":200,"type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/z316q488p/full/400,/0/default.jpg","width":400,"type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/z316q488p/full/800,/0/default.jpg","width":800,"type":"image/jpeg"}]},{"metadata":{"@type":"http://schema.org/EBook","title":"China's Economic Development: The Interplay of Scarcity and Ideology","author":"Eckstein, Alexander